'''Hochigai Shrine''' (方違神社, Hochigai Jinja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Sakai-ku, Sakai|ja|堺区|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sakai, Osaka|ja|堺市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Osaka Prefecture. Locally known as "Hochigaisan," the shrine holds the status of a former {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}}. Its enshrined deity is Hochigai Sachi Okami (かたたがえさちおおかみ). The shrine has long been revered for its power to ward off calamities related to directions, land features, and house orientations.

== History ==

According to shrine tradition, the shrine was established during the 8th year of {{ill|Emperor Sujin|ja|崇神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}'s reign (December 29, 90 BCE). It is said that the Emperor sent Mononobe no Ōmoro Suminomikoto to the Chinu no Ishizuhara area to enshrine {{ill|Susanoo|ja|スサノオ|12=draft|12=draft}}. This event marks the origin of the shrine.

Later, during {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|12=draft|12=draft}}'s conquest of the Three Kingdoms of Korea, she is said to have invoked the protection of the {{ill|Tenjin Chigi|ja|天神地祇|12=draft|12=draft}} against directional calamities at this location, achieving victory. {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} is also recorded to have enshrined Susanoo, the Tenjin Chigi, the Sumiyoshi deities, and Empress Jingū at this site. This shrine became known as "Hochigai Ōyosami no Kamutsuyashiro," commonly referred to as Hochigai Shrine.

The site, located on the boundary of the former provinces of {{ill|Settsu|ja|摂津国|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kawachi|ja|河内国|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Izumi|ja|和泉国|12=draft|12=draft}}, was considered a place without directional affiliations, making it a prominent location for directional warding rituals.

